<TITLE> Indian barriers cost US farmers millions: US study </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Dec 12, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - US farmers and food manufacturers lose millions of dollars in sales to India each year because of that country's high tariffs and other trade barriers, a US trade panel said on Friday. "The report makes it clear that India imposes a lot of barriers to imports of US agricultural products," Senator Charles Grassley said in a statement welcoming the US International Trade Commission report. Senate Finance Committee Chairman Max Baucus urged US trade negotiators to use the report's findings "to redouble their efforts to remove these barriers through vigorous trade negotiations and increased trade facilitation." The report, requested by Baucus and Grassley, puts pressure on US Trade Representative Ron Kirk to insist India make meaningful new agricultural market openings as part of the Doha round of world trade talks. India has resisted US demands for significant farm tariff cuts, arguing that would threaten the livelihood of its hundreds of millions of subsistence farmers. US negotiators believe India, a country of 1.2 billion people with a growing middle class, could open its market to more imports without endangering those farm
